snippet.textDisplay: i ran cross-country in highschool...one race was at at park that included crossing a muddy creek bed. By the time runners scrambled up the steep muddy slopes my shoes were so caked with thick, sticky,  heavy mud, it felt like barbells strapped to my feet. The rest of the race was mostly soft grass or packed earth trails... so i kicked off my mud laden shoes and ran the last mile barefoot. It felt amazing...my coach even said my entire stride changed & improved. if the terrain were always so ammenable i wudve kept racing that way.

snippet.textDisplay: First of all its the carbon pleating not the Zoom X foam that makes the Vaporfly next%/4%/Alphafly fast. The zoom X foam plays into the see saw-like shape of the shoe, which allows the runner to have more movements as they stride across the ground. Additionally, there are different versions of the Vaporfly, the first version was the 4% which was quickly replaced by the next% (the one you talk about in your video), finally, that was recently replaced by the Alphafly a quite interesting shoe. I don't think that it's the Vaporflys in general that caused the controversy but the carbon pleating technology which gives runners a boost.
snippet.textOriginal: First of all its the carbon pleating not the Zoom X foam that makes the Vaporfly next%/4%/Alphafly fast. This is why mat pat concluded heel striking is most efficient while looking at marathon runners.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here's why I've been a toe runner for the past 10 years:
Our legs are designed to act like a multi-lever spring. The more that you can utilize the natural spring motion of your legs, the more efficient (and coincidentally less tiring) the exercise of running becomes. The human leg/torso combination allows for three separate 'springs' to work in unison. The lowest one is your calf muscle, which operates the lever joint of your ankle; the thigh muscle, which operated the lever joint of your knee; and the buttox/hamstring, which operates the lever joint of your hips. If you heelstrike, this eliminates the possible lever/spring action from your ankle and calf, and thus you rely on the spring action of your knees and hips.


Side note: I'm not properly educated in sport science or physiology, so I can't back up these claims with any hard data off the top of my head, but I can say for certain that my running pain and shin splints only occur when I stop toe running and transfer over to heelstrikes. It's consistent and repeatable, so at least for me, this is how it works.
